div.div: This is a useful way to represent a trained network (with sample value states) because it shows a clear trajectory between initial attribute values (vector passed in), interim attribute values (attributes pooled into other attributes, just like attributes accrete into types), and the functions used to aggregate them.

Having another copy of the state for the same category where the positions are changed but the output is the same would be a way to remove the idea of neuron input/output trajectory (from start to final value) having a unique meaning, which implies the ideas of data augmentation & of similar data having different positions, rather than neuron layer trajectory (relationship between values in different layers) having meaning.

Having another copy of the state for the same category to illustrates how various error types can occur because of inaccurate parameters like threshold values or activation functions would be another good visual.

An abstract value trajectory from input to output (with position of original neurons removed) would be a good learning tool to illustrate the trajectory pattern permutations possible in a particular network structure.

div.div: How would you generate this representation as a good explainer of the neural network idea?
It simplifies the neural network to important interfaces (value state) while permuting the object in that interface (value) to be in a recognizable format (vector they fed into the network).
- recognizable terms for the audience (semantic map)
- relevant terms for the audience (beginner objects/attributes/rules aren't included in an expert representation)
- identifies the right structures to represent key concepts
- retains the information about the object that is necessary to connect the representation with the original form (keeping function links between nodes)
- keeps the representation mappable to the original neural network: the overall shape & position of attributes is the same, although some attributes are missing or are filled in with values
- clear labels
- labels across key differences in values (important different layers)
- displays key functions (pooling, application, summing)
- displays key attributes (inactive nodes below a threshold)
- implied attributes left out can be derived from the retained information (the activation function is implied by the threshold that deactivates some nodes)
- error types displayed

- doesn't skip links between objects that offer foundational understanding (core functions, core concepts) like the calculation of vector * weight for the input or sum(previous calculated value * weights) for the interim layers
- doesn't include objects/attributes/rules without structure (the concept of relevance can be used in the interactive explanation (communicated directly) without being included in the static visual)

- identifies the right interface to frame the visual & explanation at - semi-abstract, includes types but some attribute values to illustrate impact of functions, identifies state a key object to represent for clarity
- a good explanation will have adjacent objects to important insights in the system: the explanation will inspire anyone who reads it to arrive at the key insights using core functions
- a good explanation identifies obvious questions

- the stakes possible in the worst case scenario of misusing the tool are made clear: adding an extra layer or extra data processing can kill someone in an AI model applied to various problem types, so a good explanation of neural networks would make that clear
- the possible distortions of the system and the reason why you would or wouldn't use that distortion:

- a distortion of type 'variance injection' on the system 'neural network' in a typically static parameter like 'activation function across nodes in a layer' would have an impact of distorting the output & active nodes sent to other nodes and optimizing for different metric types, so the final classification would be altered by the specialization in optimization of weight paths.

- other common distortions (combine, alternate, switch, transform) applied to this system and the problem spaces emerging from it would also be included in the explanation, as well as any distortion combinations that would remove any of the intents of the system ('finding prediction function').
You can generate obvious questions by:
- discrepancies that would appear to be relevant but are not.
You can generate error types by:
- invalid assumptions distributed through the system
Identify the right interface to frame it in by:
- the interface with the most variance that retains the most key concepts//objects/types/attributes/functions
Identify the right amount of detail by:

- variance that could cause confusion or misunderstanding if not included (at least two layers of initial calculations when increasing dimension for a neural network type, and one final calculation when reducing dimension)

div.div: 2. Continue investing equally in alternatives, this time through distributing all possible combinations of values to the next layer

Each active node gets to send compounded weight information to each node in the next layer, based on the relative importance of each active node. It's not a network inherently biased by position, so that only direct ancestors get to contribute.

This is a form of insurance, to diversify across all possible inputs, but it may not be enough if a value has gone beyond a threshold where it could potentially have an impact on the final output, no matter what subsequent weights are, or given what subsequent weights are.

div.div: Obvious questions at this point:
How do you tell which trajectory of weights was used if they produce the same coefficients?
This architecture doesn't remember trajectory if there are equivalent weights or equivalent weight sets between the previous layers, & if all previous nodes are active.
We keep the dimensions of the vectors the same because they're representative of the coefficients.
Under certain conditions, similar trajectories will have equivalent output (where their ancestor weights or weight sets had equivalent values).
This could mean:
- data was not standardized (images weren't rotated to put features in same locations)

- the different feature sets are independent & equally important in determining the target category (dog tail & tail wagging mean dog, just like dog ear & dog teeth mean dog), which implies redundancy (unless you need to handle input without either set)

- the different feature sets are causative (some features should be removed, like if the data included dog tail gene & a dog tail attribute, and both features led to equivalent weights in different places in the network)
- the data included enough bad data or edge cases where a bad or extreme feature measurement in some data resulted in the false illusion of a relationship between feature sets

- equivalent weights occurred at different layers, so it's unlikely to be extremely meaningful, but if the cat data consistently generates equivalent weights that generate similar enough values to dog output that it's not a good model (like if data included enough cats & dogs that look like the other category), either the network parameters need to be adjusted or the data was distorted or corrupted in some way.
- it's a random coincidence

- if attributes are collapsed too much in the data (teeth size, missing teeth count collapsed to total teeth surface area in proportion to rest of mouth) that could misidentify an animal if it's aggregated with other mis-identifications between over-collapsed features.

It's important to identify the symmetries in the network input params (layer count), network output params (weights, bias) data, & data states while traversing network that could give the false illusion of equivalence.
There may be overlap with error types from permuted assumptions, but there may also be embedded assumptions that are revealed in these false symmetries.

Given common distortion functions of the network objects, it's possible to derive reasons for
additional distortions not yet explored.
- is there a reason to apply a weight vector instead of a weight per link? (making a bet that some features are more important by default)
- is there a reason to reverse or loop direction inside the network? (data just under activation threshold)
- is there a reason to allowing swapping of nodes in the network under certain test data conditions? (to use backup path if some data condition is not met)

div.div: Each node represents an alternate state of the input feature vector.
Layers with more nodes than the previous layer add additional attribute value sets.
Layers with fewer nodes gather transform combinations from more possible values (transform of A1, transform of A2, transform of A3, transform of A4)

The interim state values of features in each node represent key differentiating values, which may average (across all training data) to be a good threshold candidate. When cat tooth value gets to 0.2, there's a phase shift or attribute intersection or symmetry.

div.div: Why distort a weight by another set of weights? This is like applying a set of transforms and then applying another set of transforms. Why not just apply one that's composed of the two?

Each additional weight application acts on the previous weight combination's activation function output - so each incremental operation gives another opportunity to reach the threshold if the weight set is going to be deactivated.

div.div: After the first calculation from feature inputs to the next layer (A1), what about the next layer, where the previous layer doesn't directly map to input features and the previous outputs are activation function values?

After A1 is calculated, you have an output between 0 and 1 indicating whether the total value passed a test in your activation function. If it passed, it gets propagated as an input to the next layer. So the first function applied to 0.5 * 5 + 0.1 * 10 + 0.2 * 15 produces an output 6.5 that's input to the activation test. If it passes, the output value is propagated the same way.

6.5 (a fake value generated by fake inputs that are integers for clarity, which would normally be between 0 and 1) input to the activation function (resulting in some value like 0.7, which passes because it's above the activation threshold of 0.5) gets passed to the next layer as an input to multiply by the weight coefficient.
So 6.5 is promoted to B1 after being multiplied by the weight between A1 and B1 (0.1).
What does this mean: what's the reason why you'd do that process after applying weights to your initial input feature values?

You start with identifying attribute values (5 tooth, 10 tail, 15 noise range (meow or bark)) and now you have weighted versions of those values (2.5 tooth, 1 tail, 3 noise range - because your network had an opinion on the importance of those features after training). The ratios between the values have changed because of those weights applied. What used to be a 1:2:3 relationship is now a 5:2:6 relationship, which produced a total value of 6.5 when the original inputs were used as variable values. 6.5 stores the overall vector between those ratios, rather than the ratio relationships themselves. You lose the information of 5:2:6 between the values that is created by the application of weights to your original function (x + y + z indicating the polynomial explaining the tooth + tail + noise relationship to the species).

If that value passes the activation test (which tests for relevance in the form of difference), that implies the parameters of the network, including the activation function, have determined that this value is relevant & capable of contributing to the final classification (the value is different enough to contribute).

If it passes the activation test (If 6.5 > 5, which is the fake threshold value I've chosen for this example), then it's an input to the next weighted sum for each of the nodes in the next layer. 6.5/10 is weighted by 0.1 and added to the other activation outputs once they're weighted accordingly.

What does it mean for an activation output to be weighted? That indicates the model has determined that this sequence of weights (the path of weights from the initial input layer up to that point) so far has a degree of contribution to the final classification estimated by that weight which is being applied to the activation output.
This is extended to the largest layer, and then the activation outputs start to be pooled or otherwise processed.
The inputs of later node layers shouldn't be confused with the original input features. What you're feeding into later layers is the assessment of the contribution of each weight path.
